{"compliance_id": "df7b7720-5540-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "document_type": "Incident", "document_url": "https://data.epa.ie/leap/api/v1/Incident/byid?incident_id=df7b7720-5540-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "title": "", "description": "Exceedance of 30minute ELV on 27th & 28th May 2025 on A2-3 stack", "submission_date": "", "status": "Closed", "metadata": "{\"incidentid\": \"df7b7720-5540-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a\", \"type\": \"Incident\", \"reference\": \"INCI030430\", \"subject\": \"Breach of ELV\", \"status\": \"Closed\", \"licenceid\": \"81098567-1a89-45c0-a344-0668da16097f\", \"licenceprofileid\": \"77e11786-8292-4f95-8724-32e3e816d005\", \"complianceinvestigationid\": null, \"incidentcategory\": \"1. Minor\", \"nature\": \"Breach of ELV\", \"vulnerablereceptors\": \"None\", \"receptors\": \"Air\", \"likelihoodofreoccurence\": \"Low\", \"likelycause\": \"Failure of abatement equipment (not WWTP)\", \"newrecurring\": \"New\", \"datenotified\": \"2025-06-03T00:00:00\", \"closeddate\": \"2025-06-25T00:00:00\", \"approximatestart\": \"2025-05-27T19:30:00\", \"firstnoticed\": \"2025-05-27T19:30:00\", \"finishtime\": \"2025-05-28T15:00:00\", \"notifiedparties\": \"\", \"dischargepoint\": \"Yes\", \"emissionpointname\": \"P0110-03 - A2-3\", \"uncontrolledrelease\": \"n/a\", \"description\": \"Exceedance of 30minute ELV on 27th & 28th May 2025 on A2-3 stack\", \"otherrelevantinformation\": \"The valve seals were due for full replacement during the scheduled shutdown this July and this seal leakage was unexpected at this time.\", \"impactonenvironment\": \"None\", \"activityinprogress\": \"The increase in emissions that caused the 3 x 30minute exceedances have been identified at valve leakage from the thermal oxidizer. The first exceedance on 27 May was a symptom of  relatively higher emissions noted that week, which on review appears to have commenced on the on the previous Sunday while the site was shut. In response to this exceedance the RTO valves were adjusted by Maintenance, however, this appears to have made the emissions worse resulting in the two exceedances immediately after that adjustment. This indicated to maintenance that the issue was valve leakage and that the valve seals needed to be replaced. Production had already been reduced to prevent further exceedances, and then the decision was made to stop production fully the RTO to repair the valve seals. \\r\\n27 May @ 19:00 to 19:30 @ 43mg/m3\\r\\n28 May @ 13:00 to 13:30 @ 60mg/m3\\r\\n28 May @ 13:30 to 14:00 @ 49mg/m3 \", \"dischargedetails\": null}"}

metadata_json:
{"compliance_id": "51d25d91-5340-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "document_type": "Site Updates/Notifications", "document_url": "https://data.epa.ie/leap/api/v1/LicenseeReturns/byid?lr_id=51d25d91-5340-f011-a373-0050568a2d1a", "title": "Response to NCO32172 Non-notification of incidents", "description": "Clare County Council have employed IBSL to monitor Land fill gas at Doora.
Please see response below from IBSL. 


Subject: RE: Doora perimeter well non-compliance
 

 
I have looked back at the past 18 months of gas samples taken from Perimeter 2 (Camogie Pitch) in Doora. On no other occasion has there been an exceedance of the licence limit on CO2 at this sample point. I’m confident that the value of 7.0% CO2 recorded on 9th October 2024 should read 0.7% CO2 (it was entered into the worksheet incorrectly). I have confidence in this because I would have been immediately made aware of a licence exceedance should one have occurred – and I was not. 
 
Anthony Power
Irish Biotech Systems
Unit W10C,
Ladytown Business Park,
Naas,
Co. Kildare.
W91 YC93
IRELAND.

As per our IE Licence Schedule B.6 Ambient Monitoring, B.6.3 Soil Monitoring, Table B.6-3, MSD Ireland (Ballydine) are required to undertake soil sampling every ten years for Relevant Hazardous Substances at the monitoring locations in the Baseline Report submitted on 20th October 2022 or at alternate monitoring locations as approved by the Agency.  
  
The 15no. Relevant Hazardous Substances in relation to soil and groundwater monitoring onsite were agreed with the Agency following our submission LR016685 ‘Review and Risk Assessment of Relevant Hazardous Substances’ in 2015.  
  
For our last Baseline Soil monitoring of these 15no. Relevant Hazardous Substances in 2015, MSD Ireland (Ballydine) completed a comprehensive sampling program at 30no. locations across the site – Please refer to Attachment-4-8-2-Baseline Report (submitted 20th October 2022) submitted as part of our P0011-07 Licence Application which incorporates the Baseline Soil Assessment 2015 report as Appendix C including Figure 3-Borehole locations map.  
  
For the Baseline Soil monitoring for same 15no. Relevant Hazardous Substances during 2025, MSD Ireland (Ballydine) propose to complete monitoring at 12no. of these sampling locations, chosen based on the results of the 2015 soil sampling exercise and the location of relevant hazardous substances storage onsite. Please find enclosed supporting details for our proposal including Figure 1-Borehole locations map for these 12no. sampling locations for 2025.  
  
We trust that this proposal meets with your approval, and please revert to the undersigned if any further information is needed.  
  
Yours sincerely,  
  
David O’Gorman

{"compliance_id": "cf713a51-7baa-493e-abb4-c8a01b71c27b", "document_type": "Meeting", "document_url": "https://data.epa.ie/leap/api/v1/MeetingCorrespondence/meetingbyid?meeting_id=cf713a51-7baa-493e-abb4-c8a01b71c27b", "title": "", "description": "", "submission_date": "", "status": "Closed", "metadata": "{\"meetingid\": \"cf713a51-7baa-493e-abb4-c8a01b71c27b\", \"type\": \"Meeting\", \"reference\": \"MTG000746\", \"subject\": \"Ringsend WWTP upgrade project update from Uisce \\u00c9ireann\", \"status\": \"Closed\", \"meetingdate\": \"2025-04-07T00:00:00\", \"organisationid\": \"f5545f77-3749-e211-9eb5-0050568a69e2\", \"location\": \"Online MS Teams\", \"regarding\": \"Compliance Investigations\", \"meetingtime\": \"12:00\", \"attendeesepa\": \"Lorcan Farrell, Stephen McCarthy, David Shannon\", \"attendeesnoepa\": \"Uisce \\u00c9ireann: Ringsend WWTP Upgrade Project Team, Compliance Team & Asset Operations\\n\", \"actionitems\": \"

A video conference meeting was held between the EPA and Uisce Éireann (UÉ) on 08/04/2025 from 12:00 to 12:50 approx.

\\n

During the meeting UÉ gave an update to the EPA on the phased upgrades being undertaken at Ringsend WWTP and a summary of treatment plant performance for Q1 2025.

\\n

Works on Hybrid II upgrades and sludge treatment facilities are progressing as scheduled with all primary aspects of the upgrade project due for completion by end 2025. A programme of ancillary works connected with the overall upgrade project is also being progressed with most completion dates falling within 2025.

\\n

A summary of plant performance was given. UÉ are aiming for 104 compliance samples to be taken during 2025. 10 no. samples records were recorded in the Q1 Update under compliance investigation (CI000025).  Compliance results were unavailable for the first three weeks of January. This was attributed to operational reasons (plant shutdowns) and management changeover. It is UÉ’s intention to make up the shortfall to 104 compliance samples over the year. It was acknowledged that there is a risk that TN and TP average limits may not be achieved this year. UÉ expect that performance will improve across all parameters once remaining upgraded SBR blocks come back on-line and as average air temperatures increase through the year. UÉ confirmed that higher than expected load on the plant (2.17 PE in 2024) was expected to continue increasing in 2025 and is also affecting treatment performance. Issues with the aeration system in the Capital Upgrade treatment block were also cited as a compounding factor in treatment performance and should be resolved by end April 2025.

\\n

The EPA instructed Uisce Éireann to carry out all actions necessary to comply with the waste water discharge licence.

The Agency carried out an off-site odour assessment in accordance with the EPA Air Guidance document (AG5) Odour Impact Assessment Guidance for EPA Licensed Sites, to assess odours in the vicinity of Kepak Clonee, Industrial Emissions (IE) Licence Reg. No. P0167-02 in Clonee, Co. Meath.

\\n

During the off-site assessment, persistent moderate odour was detected at a downwind location next to the site's boundary, however the location was not deemed to be a sensitive location, therefore it was not considered to be at a level that would reasonably cause impairment or, or an interference with amenities or the environment. During the post-assessment site visit, similar odour to the one detected on the downwind location was detected on site. 

\\n

The licensee was found to be in compliance with its licence at the time of the visit. One observation was raised in relation to the way the licensee is conducting their daily odour assessments.

The Agency carried out this site visit as part of the Agency’s emissions monitoring programme. The monitoring report is attached.

\\n

The monitoring recorded a number of elevated parameters in down gradient groundwater monitoring wells at the site (ref. GW4-GW6). The results for chemical oxygen demand (COD) (up to 433 mg/l) are above what would be expected for uncontaminated groundwater. Also, the results for barium (up to 150 µg/l), iron (up to 3,100 µg/l) and manganese (up to 2,400 µg/l) are above the Agency’s recommended Interim Guidance Values (100 µg/l for barium, 200 µg/l for iron and 50 µg/l for manganese) for the protection of groundwater. There is known contamination at the site as a result of a previous release of hydrocarbons to ground.

\\n

The licensee is reminded to submit a report to the Agency which includes trend graphs of all monitored parameters, as specified in site visit report ref. SV31819, by no later than the 30/07/2025.

\\n

In addition, and as specified in site visit report ref. SV31819, the licensee shall recommence surface water up stream and down stream monitoring, to include the parameters listed in Table 5.4 of the Stage 3 Corrective Action Implementation & Verification (Aftercare) Report (ref. LR070677) and commence monitoring of ammonia at these locations. The licensee shall review the source pathway receptor linkage in this regard.

\\n

\\n
